    <div class="article-section" id="overview">
      <p>Though unified under a single political framework, the population of <a href="index.html" class="wikilink">Ormandia</a> is composed of several culturally and historically distinct peoples. The two largest contemporary groups — the <strong>Ormandish</strong> and the <strong>Garroni</strong> — differ sharply in social organization, religious practice, and relationship to centralized authority, and both trace their lineage to older peoples whose names survive chiefly in scholarly texts, place-names, and a handful of surviving customs.</p>

      <p>This article surveys both the historical peoples whose migrations and conflicts shaped the foundations of the Realm, and the living cultures that continue to define Ormandian life today.</p>

