    <!-- HISTORICAL PEOPLES -->
    <div class="article-section" id="historical">
      <h2>Historical Peoples</h2>

      <div class="lore-block" id="yurma">
        <span class="lore-tag">Historical · Ancestors of the Ormandish</span>
        <h3>The Yurma Shepherd Tribes</h3>
        <p>Long before the founding of the Realm, the high plateaus north of the <a href="index.html" class="wikilink">Greymantis Range</a> were home to the <strong>Yurma</strong> — loosely affiliated clans of pastoral herders who followed seasonal grazing routes across what is now northern Thorneshire and Valdenmere. Yurma society was organized around extended kin-groups led by elected clan-elders, with disputes settled through a tradition of oral arbitration that scholars believe directly informs the Realm's modern emphasis on documented precedent and formal council.</p>
        <p>Beginning roughly a millennium before the Common Age, sustained drought in the northern plateaus drove successive waves of Yurma clans southward into the fertile Heartland Plains. Over generations, the wandering clan-elders settled into fixed seats, their kin-groups becoming the first hereditary chiefdoms — the direct ancestors of the petty kingdoms of the <a href="index.html" class="wikilink">Shattered Thrones</a> era, and ultimately of the <a href="royal-houses.html" class="wikilink">Royal Houses</a> themselves. Many Yurma religious practices, particularly their veneration of sky and weather, were absorbed into what became the Six-Fold Faith's aspects of Wind and Light.</p>
        <p>Few unmixed Yurma communities remain; their descendants are, by and large, indistinguishable from the broader Ormandish population. However, isolated upland communities in northern Thorneshire still observe certain Yurma customs — seasonal herding festivals, woven kin-tokens, and a ceremonial dialect of Old Yurma — and are recognized by ethnographers as the closest living link to the tribes.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="lore-block" id="tideborn">
        <span class="lore-tag">Historical · Ancestors of the Garroni</span>
        <h3>The Tideborn</h3>
        <p>Predating even the earliest Yurma migrations, the western archipelagos and rocky coastlines along the <a href="index.html" class="wikilink">Craedic Sea</a> were inhabited by a seafaring people whose own name for themselves is lost to history; Ormandish chroniclers, working from fragmentary trade records, refer to them as the <strong>Tideborn</strong>. Unlike the Yurma, the Tideborn left few written records, communicating instead through an elaborate tradition of knot-script — patterns of knotted cord used to record voyages, debts, and oaths, a handful of examples of which survive in the collections of the <a href="#" class="wikilink">Cartographer's Guild</a>.</p>
        <p>The Tideborn maintained scattered island holds rather than a unified state, and resisted absorption into the expanding Yurma-descended kingdoms for centuries through superior seamanship and an intimate knowledge of the archipelago's treacherous currents. Beginning around the time of the <a href="index.html" class="wikilink">First Unification</a>, waves of mainlanders displaced by the era's wars sought refuge among the Tideborn islands, gradually intermarrying with and being absorbed into the existing island communities.</p>
        <p>The resulting blended culture — Tideborn seacraft and island holds combined with mainland language and metalwork — is the direct ancestor of the modern Garroni.</p>
      </div>
    </div>

    <!-- CONTEMPORARY PEOPLES -->
    <div class="article-section" id="contemporary">
      <h2>Contemporary Peoples</h2>

      <div class="culture-profile ormandish" id="ormandish">
        <div class="culture-header">
          <div class="culture-emblem">⚖</div>
          <div class="culture-title-block">
            <div class="culture-name">The Ormandish</div>
            <div class="culture-tagline">"What is not written is not yet true"</div>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="culture-body">
          <p>The Ormandish are the dominant culture across the majority of the seven countries, descended primarily from the settled <a href="#yurma" class="wikilink">Yurma</a> chiefdoms of the Heartland Plains. Over the centuries following the <a href="index.html" class="wikilink">First Unification</a>, Ormandish society developed its defining characteristic: an extensive, deeply entrenched system of hereditary nobility intertwined with a sprawling written bureaucracy. Where the Yurma settled disputes through oral arbitration among elders, the Ormandish settled them through charters, precedents, and the slow grinding machinery of court and council — a transition scholars term the <em>Long Codification</em>, a process not fully complete until well after the <a href="index.html" class="wikilink">Sundering Wars</a>.</p>

          <p>Ormandish identity today is closely bound up with the structures examined elsewhere in this Codex: the <a href="royal-houses.html" class="wikilink">Royal Houses</a>, the broader <a href="royal-houses.html#peerage" class="wikilink">peerage of Dukes, Margraves, Counts, and Barons</a>, and the Compact's web of law and precedent. Common tongue serves as the everyday language of trade and administration, while High Ormanic — a more formal register descended from ceremonial Yurma speech — remains the language of law, scholarship, and the Six-Fold Faith's liturgy. Ormandish religious practice tends toward orthodox observance of all six Aspects, with regional preferences (Stone in Ironmark, Flame in Emberfall) layered atop a shared core of festivals and rites.</p>

          <p>Socially, Ormandish culture places considerable weight on lineage, written record, and formal title — a tendency outsiders sometimes characterize as obsessive.</p>

          <div class="quote-block">
            "An Ormandish merchant would rather lose the sale than fail to file the paperwork for it."
            <cite>— Common saying among Garroni traders</cite>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="culture-meta">
          <div class="culture-meta-item"><span class="meta-label">Population</span><span class="meta-value">~11.5 million</span></div>
          <div class="culture-meta-item"><span class="meta-label">Languages</span><span class="meta-value">Common, High Ormanic</span></div>
          <div class="culture-meta-item"><span class="meta-label">Ancestry</span><span class="meta-value">Yurma Shepherd Tribes</span></div>
          <div class="culture-meta-item"><span class="meta-label">Structure</span><span class="meta-value">Nobility &amp; Bureaucracy</span></div>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="culture-profile garroni" id="garroni">
        <div class="culture-header">
          <div class="culture-emblem">⚓</div>
          <div class="culture-title-block">
            <div class="culture-name">The Garroni</div>
            <div class="culture-tagline">"The sea keeps its own ledgers"</div>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="culture-body">
          <p>The Garroni are a seafaring people inhabiting the western archipelagos, scattered coastal enclaves, and a handful of contested "Free Ports" along the Craedic coast — territories that fall nominally within <a href="countries.html#craedmoor" class="wikilink">Craedmoor</a>'s borders but have never been fully integrated into Ormandish administrative or legal structures. Descended from the blending of the ancient <a href="#tideborn" class="wikilink">Tideborn</a> with mainland refugee populations, the Garroni maintain a culture defined as much by what it resists as by what it practices.</p>

          <p>Garroni society is organized around ship-crews and island holds rather than noble houses; authority is held by <strong>Wave-Captains</strong> (commanders of trading or raiding vessels) and <strong>Tide-Mothers</strong> (matriarchal heads of island holds, responsible for resource allocation, dispute resolution, and — when necessary — alliance-making between holds). There is no Garroni monarch, and no single Garroni settlement holds authority over the others; cooperation between holds is negotiated case-by-case, typically at gatherings called <strong>Tide-Moots</strong>.</p>

          <p>The Garroni relationship with the rest of the Realm is famously, deliberately ambiguous. Garroni vessels engage extensively in trade — Craedmoor's merchant houses depend on Garroni shipping for routes through the archipelago's most dangerous channels — while simultaneously maintaining a long tradition of raiding vessels that fail to observe Garroni-recognized "courtesies": informal but rigorously enforced rules governing which ships may pass unmolested. The <a href="#" class="wikilink">High Council</a> has, at various points, attempted to formally classify Garroni raiding as piracy under Compact law; the Garroni response, recorded in the proceedings of the 644 A.C. council session, was reportedly to ask which specific Garroni government the Council intended to serve the ruling to.</p>

          <p>Garroni spiritual practice centers overwhelmingly on the Sea Aspect of the <a href="index.html" class="wikilink">Six-Fold Faith</a>, observed through a distinct set of rites — the <strong>Garroni Rite</strong> — that mainland clergy regard as unorthodox at best. The Garroni Cant, a language related to but substantially diverged from Common, remains the primary tongue of most island holds, though most Wave-Captains and Tide-Mothers are fluent in Common for trade purposes.</p>

          <div class="quote-block teal">
            "Sign nothing you cannot throw overboard."
            <cite>— Traditional Garroni saying, often quoted (with some irritation) by Ormandish trade negotiators</cite>
          </div>
        </div>
