    <!-- MINOR PEOPLES -->
    <div class="article-section" id="minor">
      <h2>Minor &amp; Regional Peoples</h2>

      <div class="minor-people">
        <div class="minor-card" id="emberkin">
          <h3>The Emberkin</h3>
          <p>The arid eastern plateaus of <a href="countries.html#emberfall" class="wikilink">Emberfall</a>, beyond the irrigated valleys governed from Char Citadel, are home to the Emberkin — nomadic herding clans who travel the plateaus following routes tied to seasonal rains and the migration of fire-glass-producing volcanic vents. Emberkin society shares linguistic and religious roots with the broader Ormandish population — they too venerate the Flame Aspect — but have resisted settlement and the extension of Embervane administrative authority for generations. Relations with House Embervane have ranged from uneasy trade partnership to open conflict, a tension <a href="royal-houses.html" class="wikilink">Duke Tobias Vane</a> of the Ember Reaches has more recently sought to ease through direct diplomacy.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="minor-card" id="fae">
          <h3>The Fae Peoples</h3>
          <p>The Mountain Fae of the Greymantis Range and the Sylvan Fae of the Sylmaran Deepwood are not considered "peoples" in the same administrative sense as the Ormandish or Garroni — neither holds Compact citizenship as such — but their influence on Ormandian culture, particularly in <a href="countries.html#sylmara" class="wikilink">Sylmara</a>, is profound. The Sylvan Fae's representation on the <a href="#" class="wikilink">Fae Conclave</a> gives them a unique formal political role unmatched by any other non-Ormandish people in the Realm.</p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>

    <!-- RELATIONS -->
    <div class="article-section" id="relations">
      <h2>Cultural Relations &amp; Tensions</h2>
      <p>The defining cultural tension in contemporary Ormandia remains the unresolved status of Garroni territories within the Compact framework. Successive Margraves of the Saltmere Reaches — currently <a href="royal-houses.html#saltmere" class="wikilink">Margrave Bryndor Saltmere</a> — have served as the de facto channel for negotiation between Craedmoor's government and the Garroni holds, maintaining an informal peace that neither side has any interest in formalizing, since formalization would require one side to make concessions the other has never offered.</p>
      <p>A second, quieter tension concerns the slow erosion of pre-Ormandish cultural practices — Yurma customs in northern Thorneshire, Tideborn knot-script among older Garroni Tide-Mothers — as Common tongue and Ormandish administrative practice spread even into traditionally resistant communities. Ethnographers at the <a href="#" class="wikilink">Valdenmere Academy</a> have in recent decades made increasingly urgent calls for the documentation of these traditions before living memory of them fades entirely.</p>

